    <question>
        <prompt>What was the significance of the "New South" movement in the 1880s?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">It promoted industrialization and economic diversification in the South</option>
            <option letter="b">It sought to restore plantation agriculture</option>
            <option letter="c">It opposed railroad development</option>
            <option letter="d">It focused on political reform only</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>The New South movement, led by Henry Grady and others, advocated for Southern industrialization, railroad expansion, and economic diversification beyond agriculture to rebuild the post-Civil War Southern economy.</explanation>
    </question>
    <question>
        <prompt>How did the growth of the textile industry affect the Southern economy?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">It created new manufacturing jobs but often exploited workers through low wages and child labor</option>
            <option letter="b">It primarily benefited Northern investors</option>
            <option letter="c">It had minimal impact on employment</option>
            <option letter="d">It focused only on cotton exports</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>The growth of Southern textile mills provided new industrial jobs but often relied on exploitative practices, including low wages, long hours, and the widespread use of child labor.</explanation>
    </question>
    <question>
        <prompt>What role did Henry Grady play in promoting the New South?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">He was a leading spokesman who promoted Southern industrialization through speeches and writings</option>
            <option letter="b">He focused on agricultural reforms</option>
            <option letter="c">He opposed Northern investment</option>
            <option letter="d">He promoted racial equality</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>As editor of the Atlanta Constitution, Henry Grady was the leading spokesman for the New South, promoting industrialization and economic modernization through influential speeches and editorials.</explanation>
    </question>
    <question>
        <prompt>What impact did the development of Birmingham, Alabama have on Southern industry?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">It became a major steel production center due to its unique combination of coal, iron ore, and limestone deposits</option>
            <option letter="b">It remained primarily agricultural</option>
            <option letter="c">It focused on textile manufacturing</option>
            <option letter="d">It had minimal industrial growth</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>Birmingham emerged as a major industrial center because it contained all three raw materials needed for steel production - coal, iron ore, and limestone - making it the South's leading steel producer.</explanation>
    </question>
